<header class="header">
  <h1>Best Watermelon Support Net for Vertical Growing</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    Vertical watermelon growing saves space, but the fruit needs support before it becomes a problem.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    <strong>For most gardeners, the best watermelon support net is a strong, flexible net or sling that supports the fruit evenly without restricting growth.</strong>
  </p>
  <p>
    Watermelons can be grown vertically on a trellis, but as the fruit develops, the vine alone cannot support the weight. Without additional support, the fruit can pull away from the vine or fall.
  </p>
  <p>
    A proper support net prevents that stress while allowing the fruit to grow naturally.
  </p>
</header>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Quick Answer: What Works Best?</h2>

  <div class="quickAnswerBox">
    <ul class="plainList">
      <li><strong>Best overall:</strong> soft netting that distributes weight evenly.</li>
      <li><strong>Best for large fruit:</strong> wider, deeper support slings.</li>
      <li><strong>Best setup:</strong> attached securely to the trellis above the fruit.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <p>
    The goal is to support the fruit without stressing the vine.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Why Watermelons Need Support When Trellised</h2>

  <p>
    Unlike smaller fruits, watermelons gain weight quickly as they mature. The vine can support early growth, but later stages often exceed what the stem can handle.
  </p>

  <p>
    Without support, the vine can stretch, crack, or break entirely.
  </p>

  <p>
    Supporting the fruit early prevents damage later.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Makes a Good Support Net</h2>

  <h3>Strength</h3>
  <p>
    The material must hold the full weight of the fruit without tearing.
  </p>

  <h3>Flexibility</h3>
  <p>
    A flexible net conforms to the shape of the melon as it grows.
  </p>

  <h3>Breathability</h3>
  <p>
    Airflow reduces moisture buildup and helps prevent rot.
  </p>

  <h3>Secure Attachment</h3>
  <p>
    The net should tie easily into your trellis system.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>Best Types of Watermelon Support Nets</h2>

  <div class="decisionTableWrap">
    <table class="decisionTable">
