  <p>
    Softer materials generally perform better than rigid ones.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>When to Install the Net</h2>

  <p>
    Install support when the fruit is still small but clearly developing. Waiting too long increases the risk of stress or breakage.
  </p>

  <p>
    Early support allows the net to carry the weight as the fruit grows.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>How to Attach It Properly</h2>

  <ol class="plainList">
    <li>Place the net under the developing fruit.</li>
    <li>Attach both sides to the trellis above.</li>
    <li>Adjust so the fruit is gently supported.</li>
    <li>Avoid tight pressure against the vine.</li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    The support should lift slightly, not squeeze.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="guideSection">
  <h2>What Most Gardeners Get Wrong</h2>

  <h3>Waiting Too Long</h3>
  <p>
    Late support is less effective and risks damage.
  </p>

  <h3>Using Weak Materials</h3>
  <p>
    Thin nets can fail under full fruit weight.
  </p>

  <h3>Restricting Growth</h3>
  <p>
    Tight supports can deform or damage the melon.
  </p>

  <h3>Poor Attachment</h3>
  <p>
    Loose connections shift under load.
  </p>
</section>

